SIMPLE: nostril
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nostril
<hw>Nos"tril</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>nosethril</ets>, <ets>nosethirl</ets>, AS.
<ets>nos⟦thorn⟧yrl</ets>; <ets>nos</ets> for <ets>nosu</ets> nose +
<ets>⟦thorn⟧yrel</ets> opening, hole, from <ets>⟦thorn⟧yrel</ets>
pierced, for <ets>⟦thorn⟧yrhel</ets>, fr. <ets>purh</ets> through.
⟦root⟧261. See <er>Nose</er>, and <er>Through</er>, and cf.
<er>Thrill</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the external openings of
the nose, which give passage to the air breathed and to secretions from
the nose and eyes; one of the anterior nares.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In sperm whales, porpoises, and allied animals, there is
only one nostril, which is situated on the top of the head and called a
<xex>spiracle</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Perception; insight; acuteness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methinks a man⟦br⟧
Of your sagacity and clear <qex>nostril</qex> should⟦br⟧
Have made another choice.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nostrum</ent>⟦br⟧
